{
  "texts": [
    "The generalizability of the graph pooling method is reflected in the fact that the pooling method maintains excellent processing performance when the structure of the graph data changes (Li et al. 2202).",
    "Since the graph data is sparse, i.e., most nodes lack direct connections to each other, the algorithm is susceptible to noise and outliers when extracting features, which may lead to a degradation of the model's performance when processing new data.",
    "In addition, the topological variability of graph data is also a challenge.",
    "Different graph data have different topologies, which makes it difficult to directly apply trained graph pooling methods to other datasets.",
    "When faced with new types of data, the model often needs to be retrained, which not only increases the computational cost but also limits the applicability of the model."
  ]
}